 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>1</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Stock
options vest in three equal installments, except for stock options granted on June&nbsp;1, 2008 and July&nbsp;11, 2011, which vest in
equal installments over five years. Vesting continues upon the participant's termination of employment due to Retirement, Disability (each as defined in the Stock Benefit Plan) or death, as
follows: </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT>
<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Retirement: Stock options to continue to vest in accordance with the vesting schedule and can be exercised until the
expiration date. However, if death occurs before the award expires, the unvested stock options are forfeited. If death occurs within three months after Retirement, vested options can be exercised as
described below in the "death" provision. If death occurs after three months from Retirement, vested options can be exercised until the option expiration date.  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Disability: Stock options continue to vest and are exercisable until the earlier of: (i)&nbsp;one year after termination
of employment; and (ii)&nbsp;the option expiration date, except that if death occurs before the award expires, then unvested options are forfeited and vested options are exercisable for the period
described herein.  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Death: If death occurs during employment, or within three months after termination of employment for reasons other than
Cause, then unvested options are forfeited and vested options are exercisable until the earlier of (i)&nbsp;one year after death or (ii)&nbsp;the option expiration date. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
</DD></DL>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>57</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=64,EFW="2205348",CP="AAR CORP",DN="1",CHK=835945,FOLIO='57',FILE='DISK131:[11ZDA1.11ZDA76401]DP76401A.;9',USER='BSKELLE',CD='24-AUG-2011;20:05' -->
<A NAME="page_dp76401_1_58"> </A>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg76401a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<UL>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Certain
options listed were "reload" options, which have an exercise price equal to the NYSE closing price on the date the original option was exercised, but retain the original option expiration
date. The Company no longer grants reload options and all outstanding options have been amended to eliminate the reload provisions.  </FONT></P>

</UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>2</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>These
restricted stock awards were granted in connection with attainment of previously established performance goals under the Stock Benefit
Plan. The vesting schedules applicable to the restricted stock are as follows: </FONT></DD></DL>
 <DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;width:70%;margin-left:15%;">
<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><font size=1></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>


<!-- COMMAND=ADD_TABLEWIDTH,"100%" -->


 </FONT></P>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>*</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
8,968 shares of restricted stock granted to Mr.&nbsp;Stinson for Fiscal 2008 on May&nbsp;31, 2008 and the 13,150 shares of restricted stock granted to
him for Fiscal 2009 on May&nbsp;31, 2009 vest in equal installments over three years. <BR></FONT>
<BR>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Vesting
in restricted stock awards continues or is accelerated upon the participant's termination of employment due to Retirement, Disability (each as defined in the Stock Benefit Plan) or death as
follows: </FONT></P>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Retirement: The awards continue to vest in accordance with the vesting schedule.  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Disability or death: On or before the third anniversary of grant, the difference between one-half of the total
award shares and the number of award shares already vested will vest as of such termination; after the third anniversary of grant, all award shares vest as of such termination. <BR>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD></DL>
</DD></DL>
</UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>3</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>This
column shows the market value of the unvested restricted stock held by the named executive officers, based on a price of $26.39 per share
(the closing market price of the Common Stock on May&nbsp;31, 2011, the last business day of Fiscal 2011). </FONT></DD></DL>

<DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:10%;">
 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>1</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>This
amount represents the difference between the closing market price of the Common Stock on the date of exercise and the exercise price,
multiplied by the number of shares covered by the option.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>2</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>These
amounts represent the closing market price of the Common Stock on the date of vesting, multiplied by the number of shares that vested. </FONT></DD></DL>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ds76401_retirement_program_benefits"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ds76401_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Retirement Program Benefits    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company provides defined benefit pension benefits under the SKERP and the Retirement Plan. The following table shows the years of service
currently credited to each named executive officer under the applicable plan and the present value of the accumulated benefit payable under the applicable plan to each named executive officer at the
earliest age an unreduced benefit is payable. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ds76401_fiscal_2011_pension_benefits"> </A>

 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>1</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Number
of Years of Credited Service as of May&nbsp;31, 2005, the date the Retirement Plan was frozen.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>2</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Amounts
shown in this column are calculated as of May&nbsp;31, 2011, which is the measurement date for reporting purposes in the Company's
Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for Fiscal 2011. See Note&nbsp;6 to the Consolidated Financial Statements contained in the Company's Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for
an explanation of the assumptions made by the Company in determining the amounts reported in this column.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>3</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Messrs.&nbsp;Poulton,
Stinson and Regan do not participate in the defined benefit portion of the SKERP or in the Retirement Plan. </FONT></DD></DL>
 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> SKERP&nbsp;&#151; Defined Benefit Portion  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company provides supplemental retirement benefits to certain executives and key employees under the SKERP. The SKERP, which is a
non-qualified plan, contains a defined benefit portion and a defined contribution portion (discussed below). Only Mr.&nbsp;Storch and Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko participate in the defined
benefit portion of the SKERP, the material terms and conditions of which include the following: </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Benefit Accruals:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the defined benefit portion of the SKERP, benefits were accrued until October&nbsp;1, 2001 pursuant to a formula that provides a monthly
single life annuity at retirement at age 65 equal to: (i)&nbsp;<SUP>1</SUP>/<SMALL>12</SMALL> of 60% (50% for Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko) of Final Average Earnings less (ii)&nbsp;the monthly benefit payable under
the Company's Retirement Plan determined as of October&nbsp;1, </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>60</FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg76401a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<BR>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>2001.
For purposes of this benefit formula, (i)&nbsp;"Final Average Earnings" is defined as <SUP>1</SUP>/<SMALL>5</SMALL> of a participant's Compensation during the five consecutive years within the last
10&nbsp;years preceding termination of employment during which such Compensation was the highest, and (ii)&nbsp;"Compensation" is defined as the participant's income reported on
Form&nbsp;W-2, including pre-tax contributions to the Retirement Savings Plan, reduced by the income attributable to restricted stock and stock options, reimbursements or
other expense allowances and fringe benefits. Benefits accrued on and after October&nbsp;1, 2001 under the defined benefit portion of the SKERP will accrue pursuant to a formula that provides a
monthly single life annuity at retirement at age 65 equal to <SUP>1</SUP>/<SMALL>12</SMALL> of 60% (50% for Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko) of 25% of the percentage increase in the participant's base salary from
September&nbsp;30, 2001 to the date of the participant's termination of employment. The benefits accrued by Messrs.&nbsp;Storch and Romenesko as of May&nbsp;31, 2006 have been transferred to the
defined contribution portion of the SKERP and are held in an account established and maintained thereunder for each participant. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Benefits
accrued under the defined benefit portion of the SKERP for all other participants ceased on October&nbsp;1, 2001 and were distributed to them in a lump sum as soon as practicable
thereafter. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Benefit Entitlement:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A participant is eligible to receive the benefit accrued under the SKERP following termination of employment when he reaches age 65. If a
participant terminates employment after he reaches age 55 and his age plus years of service equal or exceed 62, benefits will be paid on the date of his termination or on a date no later than
15&nbsp;years after termination of employment, as previously specified by the participant. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Form of Benefit Payment:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Each participant has previously elected to have the remainder of his retirement benefit paid in a lump sum. The assumptions set forth in
the Company's Retirement Plan will be used to convert the retirement benefits from an annuity payment to a lump sum. The participant may change the time or form of payment in accordance with
procedures set forth in the SKERP. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Forfeiture Events:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A participant will forfeit the retirement benefit if his employment is terminated due to theft, embezzlement, fraud or willful misconduct in the
performance of his duties that materially injures the Company, or if during employment or the one-year period thereafter the participant violates the covenant not to compete contained in
the SKERP. As a condition to receiving his retirement benefit, a participant must agree in writing to return his benefit, plus 8% interest, in the event of such forfeiture. The forfeiture provision
does not apply if the participant's termination of employment causes benefits to be paid to him under Change in Control provisions of any agreement between the participant and the Company. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Retirement Plan  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company's Retirement Plan is a tax-qualified pension plan. Benefit accruals ceased under the Retirement Plan with respect to most
participants, including the named executive officers, effective June&nbsp;1, 2005. Messrs.&nbsp;Poulton, Stinson and Regan do not participate in the Retirement Plan because their dates of hire
were
after June&nbsp;1, 2005. The material terms and conditions of the Retirement Plan as they pertain to Messrs.&nbsp;Storch and Romenesko are as follows: </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Benefit Formula:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Until January&nbsp;1, 2000, benefits were accrued pursuant to a formula that provides a monthly single life annuity at retirement at age 65
equal to 1<SUP>1</SUP>/<SMALL>2</SMALL>% of the participant's Final Average Earnings reduced by the participant's Social Security offset determined under the </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>61</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=2,SEQ=68,EFW="2205348",CP="AAR CORP",DN="1",CHK=246870,FOLIO='61',FILE='DISK131:[11ZDA1.11ZDA76401]DS76401A.;19',USER='GLOPEZA',CD='26-AUG-2011;21:05' -->
<A NAME="page_ds76401_1_62"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg76401a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<BR>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Plan,
multiplied by the participant's years of Credited Service (up to 20). Effective as of January&nbsp;1, 2000, the Plan was converted to a cash balance type of plan, subject to a "grandfather"
provision applicable to certain participants based on age and years of service. An account is maintained for each participant which consists of (i)&nbsp;an opening account balance equal to the then
present value of the benefit accrued by the participant under the prior formula as of December&nbsp;31, 1999, (ii)&nbsp;quarterly contributions made by the Company equal to a percentage of
compensation based on the participant's age and years of Credited Service, and (iii)&nbsp;quarterly interest credits made by the Company equal to 25% of the 30-year Treasury securities
interest rate for the second month preceding the beginning of each quarter. For purposes of the benefit formulae, "Final Average Earnings" and "Compensation" have the same definitions as used in the
SKERP, as discussed above. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
benefits under the Retirement Plan generally ceased accruing on June&nbsp;1, 2005, although the participants' cash balance accounts continue to be credited with interest until the benefits are
distributed. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Vesting:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Participants are eligible to receive benefits from the Retirement Plan after completing five years of Vesting Service. The named executive officers who
participate in the Retirement Plan are fully vested in their benefits. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Payment of Retirement Benefits:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Participants can elect to receive their benefits upon termination of employment or they can defer receipt of benefits until normal
retirement age (age 65). Any vested participant can elect benefits at any time after termination of employment, with the
benefit actuarially reduced to reflect payment prior to age 65. The Retirement Plan also provides for a Disability retirement benefit. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Forms of Benefit Payment:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The normal form of benefit payment for a married participant is a joint and 50% survivor annuity, and the normal form of benefit payment
for an unmarried participant is a single life annuity. Participants, with spousal consent, if applicable, can waive the normal form of benefit payment and elect to have benefits paid in various
annuity forms, which are the actuarial equivalent of the normal form, or in a lump sum. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Retirement Savings Plan:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In connection with ceasing benefits under the Retirement Plan, the Company amended its Retirement Savings Plan to provide additional
benefits, as described below in the discussion following the Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation table. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company provides non-qualified deferred compensation benefits under the defined contribution portion of the SKERP. The following
table below shows the contributions made by each named executive officer and by the Company in Fiscal 2011, the earnings accrued on the named executive officer's account balance in Fiscal 2011, and
the account balance as of May&nbsp;31, 2011. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>62</FONT></P>

 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>1</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
amount of contributions made by each named executive officer and reported in this column in respect of salary deferrals in Fiscal 2011 is
included in each named executive officer's compensation reported in the Summary Compensation Table as "Salary." The amount of contributions reported in this column also reflects deferral of cash
bonuses paid in Fiscal 2011 but earned and reported in the Summary Compensation Table for Fiscal 2010.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>2</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
amount of Company contributions reported in this column for each named executive officer is reported in the "All Other Compensation" column
in the Summary Compensation Table.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>3</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
investment earnings reported in this column for each named executive officer are not reported in the Summary Compensation Table.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>4</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
aggregate balance as of May&nbsp;31, 2011 reported in this column for each named executive officer reflects amounts that have been
previously reported as compensation in the Summary Compensation Table for Fiscal 2011 or prior years, except the following amounts of earnings included in the account balance: Mr.&nbsp;Storch,
$1,823,382; Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko, $281,855; Mr.&nbsp;Poulton, $70,217; Mr.&nbsp;Stinson, $66,881; and Mr.&nbsp;Regan, $89,802. The aggregate balance as of May&nbsp;31, 2011 also includes the
following cumulative amounts transferred from the defined benefit portion of the SKERP: Mr.&nbsp;Storch, $1,712,865; and Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko, $272,876. </FONT></DD></DL>
 </DIV>
 <P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> SKERP&nbsp;&#151; Defined Contribution Portion  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The defined contribution portion of the SKERP covers certain executives and key employees, including all of the named executive officers, and
provides the portion of a participant's benefit that cannot be paid under the Retirement Savings Plan due to Internal Revenue Code limits, including the limit on the amount of compensation that can be
taken into account in determining benefits ($245,000 in 2010 and 2011). The material terms and conditions of the defined contribution portion of the SKERP include the following: </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Contributions:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Each participant may make an election which satisfies Code Section&nbsp;409A to contribute a portion of his base salary (up to 75%) for that
calendar year that exceeds the Code's compensation limit and a portion of the bonus (up to 75%) paid to him for the Company's fiscal year beginning in such calendar year that exceeds the Code's
compensation limit. The Company makes a matching contribution under the SKERP using the formula in the Retirement Savings Plan (i.e.,&nbsp;20% of the first 5% of the participant's contributions, up
to 1% of compensation), as well as the portion of the Company's retirement benefit and profit sharing contributions that could not be made under the Savings Plan due to the Code's compensation limit.
The Company also makes annual supplemental contributions to the accounts of the Chief Executive Officer (22% of base salary and bonus), the President (16% of base salary and bonus) and other eligible </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>63</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=70,EFW="2205348",CP="AAR CORP",DN="1",CHK=378625,FOLIO='63',FILE='DISK131:[11ZDA1.11ZDA76401]DS76401A.;19',USER='GLOPEZA',CD='26-AUG-2011;21:05' -->
<A NAME="page_ds76401_1_64"> </A>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg76401a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<BR>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>named
executive officers (5% or 10% of base salary and bonus). To receive a credit of this contribution, the eligible participant must be employed as of the day before the contribution is made to the
SKERP (unless termination of employment is due to death or Disability). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Storch
and Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko also have amounts held in a supplemental account that were transferred from the defined benefit portion of the SKERP, which represent the lump sum value of
each participant's accrued benefit as of May&nbsp;31, 2006 under the defined benefit portion. These amounts are now subject to the terms and conditions of the defined contribution portion of the
SKERP. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Vesting:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A participant is fully vested in amounts attributable to his own deferral contributions, and vests in all Company contributions, except supplemental
contributions, at a rate equal to 33<SUP>1</SUP>/<SMALL>3</SMALL>% for each year of vesting service (subject to full vesting upon age 65, death or Disability). A participant vests in amounts attributable to
Company supplemental contributions (i)&nbsp;made prior to October&nbsp;17, 2007, upon the earlier of age 65, or age 57 with 15&nbsp;years of service, and (ii)&nbsp;made after
October&nbsp;17, 2007, upon the earlier of age 65, or age 55 with the sum of age and years of service equal to at least 75. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Investments:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Each participant's plan accounts are credited with earnings and losses based on investment alternatives made available by the plan committee and
selected by the participant from time to time. The investment options currently offered under the SKERP consist of 24
mutual funds including 10 "Life Cycle" fund choices. Participants may change investment elections at any time. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Distributions:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Distribution of a participant's accounts is generally made upon the participant's termination of employment or on a date no later than
15&nbsp;years after termination of employment, as previously specified by the participant. Participants were to elect by December&nbsp;31, 2005 whether their accounts are to be paid in a lump sum
or installments not to exceed 15&nbsp;years (a participant who failed to make an election will have his account paid in a lump sum). Notwithstanding the foregoing, (i)&nbsp;a participant may elect
distribution of the portion of his accounts earned and vested as of December&nbsp;31, 2004 (and earnings thereon) upon six month's advance written election or if such distribution is subject to a
10% forfeiture; (ii)&nbsp;a participant can change the time and form of payment of the portion of his accounts earned and vested after December&nbsp;31, 2004 in accordance with procedures set
forth in the plan; (iii)&nbsp;a participant can elect a distribution at any time in order to satisfy an unforeseeable hardship (as defined in the plan); and (iv)&nbsp;in the event of a potential
Change in Control of the Company (as determined by the Board), the portion of the participant's accounts earned and vested as of December&nbsp;31, 2004 (including earnings thereon) will be
distributed in an immediate lump sum. Distributions to "key employees" as defined in Code Section&nbsp;409A upon termination of employment will not be paid earlier than six months following such
termination. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Forfeiture Events:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A participant will forfeit the portion of his plan accounts attributable to Company supplemental contributions and to amounts transferred from
the defined benefit portion of the SKERP, if applicable, if his employment is terminated due to theft, embezzlement or fraud or willful misconduct in the performance of his duties that materially
injures the Company, or if during employment or the one-year period thereafter the participant violates the covenant not to compete contained in the SKERP. As a condition to receiving such
amounts, a participant must agree in writing to return such amounts, plus 8% interest, in the event of such forfeiture. The forfeiture provision does not apply if the participant's termination of
employment </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>64</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=71,EFW="2205348",CP="AAR CORP",DN="1",CHK=734513,FOLIO='64',FILE='DISK131:[11ZDA1.11ZDA76401]DS76401A.;19',USER='GLOPEZA',CD='26-AUG-2011;21:05' -->
<A NAME="page_ds76401_1_65"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><A

<BR>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>causes
benefits to be paid to him under change in control provisions of any agreement between the participant and the Company. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Retirement Savings Plan  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The Retirement Savings Plan is a tax-qualified retirement plan that covers most United States employees, including the named executive
officers. The material terms and conditions of the Retirement Savings Plan as it pertains to non-union employees are as follows: </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Contributions:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;A participant can elect to defer 1% to 75% of compensation, up to a maximum of $16,500 for 2011, or $22,500 if age 50 or older. Contributions can be
made on a pre-tax or after-tax basis, as elected by the participant. Unless a participant elects otherwise: (i)&nbsp;participation for non-union employees hired
on or after June&nbsp;1, 2007 and prior to June&nbsp;26, 2009 is automatic at a 3% deferral rate; and (ii)&nbsp;participation for non-union employees hired on or after
June&nbsp;26, 2009 is automatic at a 5% deferral rate, with automatic 1% annual increase. The Company provides a matching contribution, a profit sharing contribution and a retirement benefit
contribution. The current matching contribution is made, as of each payroll period, in an amount equal to 20% of the first 5% of the participant's contributions, up to 1% of compensation, to the Plan
for such payroll period. The profit sharing contribution is made, as of the end of each calendar year and, is based on the participant's contributions and the economic performance of the participant's
operating unit and is equal to a percentage of the participant's compensation, up to 4%. The retirement benefit contribution, which is also made as of the end of each calendar year, was added to the
Plan, effective June&nbsp;1, 2005, and is equal to a percentage of compensation, up to 4%, based on the participant's age and years of credited service. A participant must have earned one year of
service to be eligible for a retirement benefit contribution, and generally must be employed on the last day of the calendar year to receive a profit sharing contribution. Compensation for purposes of
determining contributions includes cash compensation shown as income on the participant's Form&nbsp;W-2, reduced by the participant's contributions to the plan and excluding the income
attributable to restricted stock options, reimbursements or other expense allowances and fringe benefits and subject to the Code's compensation limit ($245,000 for 2010 and 2011). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Investments:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Each participant's plan account is credited with earnings and losses based on investment alternatives made available by the plan committee and
selected by the participant from time to time. The investment options currently offered under the plan consist of 24 mutual funds including 10 "Life Cycle" fund choices. Participants may change
investment elections at any time. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Vesting:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Participants hired prior to July&nbsp;1, 1999 are fully vested in their accounts under the plan. Participants hired on or after January&nbsp;1, 1999
are fully vested in their own contribution accounts, and vest in the Company contribution accounts at a rate equal to 33<SUP>1</SUP>/<SMALL>3</SMALL>% for each year of vesting service (subject to full vesting
upon age 65, death or Disability). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Distributions:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Participants can elect distributions of the plan accounts upon termination of employment, in a lump sum, an eligible rollover distribution, or, if
early or normal retirement has been attained, in installments not to exceed 15&nbsp;years. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>65</FONT></P>

<A NAME="toc_du76401_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Potential Payments Upon Termination of Employment or a Change in Control of the Company    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company provides certain benefits to eligible employees upon certain types of termination of employment, including a termination of employment
involving a Change in Control of the Company. These benefits are in addition to the benefits to which the employees would be entitled upon a termination of employment generally (i.e.,&nbsp;vested
retirement benefits accrued as of the date of termination, stock options and restricted stock that are otherwise vested as of the date of termination and the right to elect
continued health coverage pursuant to COBRA). These benefits as they pertain to the named executive officers are as described and set forth in the tables beginning on page&nbsp;71. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Employment Agreement of David P. Storch  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company has an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Storch that provides the following severance benefits: </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Termination of Employment&nbsp;&#151; Prior to a Change in Control:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If prior to a Change in Control, either the Company terminates his employment without
Cause or Mr.&nbsp;Storch terminates his employment for Good Reason, Mr.&nbsp;Storch is entitled to: (i)&nbsp;continued payment of his base salary for 36&nbsp;months, and (ii)&nbsp;a lump sum
payment equal to three times the average of the cash incentive bonus paid to him for the preceding three fiscal years of the Company. Payments cease upon any material breach of the confidentiality and
non-compete provisions set forth in the agreement (the non-compete provisions remain in effect for the two-year period following any such termination of
employment). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Termination of Employment&nbsp;&#151; Following a Change in Control:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If Mr.&nbsp;Storch's employment is terminated within 24&nbsp;months following a
Change in Control either by the Company other than for Cause or Disability or by Mr.&nbsp;Storch for Good Reason, or if his employment terminates for any reason other than Disability or death during
the 30-day period following the 24<SUP>th</SUP>&nbsp;month after a Change in Control, he is entitled to: </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>An immediate lump sum payment equal to the sum of (A)&nbsp;any unpaid salary through the date of termination and any
unpaid bonus earned for the preceding fiscal year, (B)&nbsp;a pro rata portion of the bonus that would have been paid to him had he remained employed until the end of the fiscal year and all
performance targets were met, and (C)&nbsp;(1) if termination is within the 24-month period for other than Cause, or for Disability or Good Reason, three times his base salary and cash
bonus for either the most recently completed fiscal year prior to the termination or the preceding fiscal year, whichever produces the higher amount or (2)&nbsp;if termination is by
Mr.&nbsp;Storch during the 30-day period following the 24-month period, an amount equal to $4,747,770 (pursuant to the employment agreement, this amount reflects the
computation described in (C)(1) above, based on base salary and bonus paid in Fiscal 2010);  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Continued coverage for Mr.&nbsp;Storch and his spouse under the Company's welfare and fringe benefit plans for three
years following termination of employment (he and his spouse can elect continued medical and dental coverage pursuant to COBRA at the end of such three-year period); </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>A lump sum payment of an amount equal to the lesser of (A)&nbsp;three times the amount of Company contributions made
under the Retirement Savings Plan and the defined contribution portion of the SKERP for the calendar year preceding the year in which the </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Mr.&nbsp;Storch
is also entitled to the benefits described above under "Termination of Employment&nbsp;&#151; Prior to Change in Control" if he terminates his employment for Good Reason
after the 30<SUP>th</SUP>&nbsp;day following the 24<SUP>th</SUP>&nbsp;month after a Change in Control. The employment agreement's non-compete provisions do not apply in the case
of a termination of employment following a Change in Control. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> General:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Regardless of whether a Change of Control is involved: </FONT></P>

<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>If Mr.&nbsp;Storch's termination is due to Retirement, he and his spouse are entitled to continued coverage under the
Company's medical, dental, welfare and executive health programs for his (and his spouse's) lifetime (or until he obtains health coverage from a new employer);  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>If Mr.&nbsp;Storch's employment terminates due to Disability, he will receive payment pursuant to the Company's
Disability plans then in effect, and he will continue to receive coverage under the Company's medical, dental, and life insurance plans for three years following such termination (the employment
agreement provides that payments under the Company's Disability plans will be at a level no less favorable than that in effect on May&nbsp;31, 2010); and  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>If Mr.&nbsp;Storch's employment is terminated following the expiration of his agreement, he will be entitled to receive
the same benefits as if he were terminated without Cause by the Company prior to a Change in Control. </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>In
any event, payments under the employment agreement in connection with Mr.&nbsp;Storch's termination of employment that would be considered deferred compensation under Section&nbsp;409A of the
Internal Revenue Code will be delayed for six months following such termination to the extent necessary to comply with Section&nbsp;409A. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>For
purposes of Mr.&nbsp;Storch's employment agreement: </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>"Change
in Control" means (i)&nbsp;a person's acquisition of more than 35% of the voting power of the Company's outstanding stock, (ii)&nbsp;a merger or consolidation of the Company that results
in the holders of the voting stock immediately prior thereto holding less than 60% of the voting stock of the resulting or surviving entity, (iii)&nbsp;a sale of substantially all of the Company's
assets other than to an entity at least 80% owned by the Company, or (iv)&nbsp;the election, without the consent of the incumbent Board, of a majority of the directors then in office. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>"Cause"

the Board, or (iii)&nbsp;material breach of the employment agreement that is not cured within 30&nbsp;days of receipt of notice from the Company. </FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>"Disability"
means a physical or mental condition that has prevented Mr.&nbsp;Storch from substantially performing his duties under the employment agreement for a period of 180&nbsp;days and that
is expected to continue to render Mr.&nbsp;Storch unable to substantially perform his duties for the remaining term of the employment agreement on a full-time basis. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>"Good

of the employment agreement by the Company that is not cured within 30&nbsp;days of receipt of notice from Mr.&nbsp;Storch, or (iii)&nbsp;a relocation of his primary place of employment by 50 or
more miles. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>"Retirement"
means Mr.&nbsp;Storch's voluntary termination of employment that does not result in severance payments under the employment agreement. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Severance and Change in Control Agreements  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company has severance and change in control agreements with Messrs.&nbsp;Romenesko, Poulton and Regan and with certain other key employees. The
agreements as they pertain to these named executive officers provide for the following benefits upon the following types of employment termination: </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Termination of Employment&nbsp;&#151; Prior to a Change in Control:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If a Change in Control of the Company has not occurred and the executive's employment
is terminated by the Company other than for Cause, he is entitled to (i)&nbsp;continued salary for 12&nbsp;months or, if earlier, until he obtains comparable employment, (ii)&nbsp;any earned
bonus not yet paid for the preceding fiscal year, and (iii)&nbsp;a pro-rata portion of the bonus that would have been paid to the executive had he remained employed until the end of the
fiscal year in which the termination occurs. Any bonus will be paid in a lump sum on the later of the time bonuses are paid to other officers and the end of the severance period (with interest at the
prime rate plus 1% from the earlier of such dates). If the executive terminates his employment, or if the Company terminates the executive's employment for Cause, the Company may, but is not required
to, pay the above-described severance benefits. Severance payments will cease if the executive breaches the confidentiality or non-compete provisions in the agreement, which are in effect
for the one-year severance period. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Termination of Employment&nbsp;&#151; Following a Change in Control:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If the executive's employment is terminated within 18&nbsp;months following a
Change in Control by the Company other than for Cause or Disability or by the executive for Good Reason, or if the executive's employment terminates for any reason other than Disability or death
during the 30-day period following the 18<SUP>th</SUP>&nbsp;month after a Change in Control, he is entitled to (i)&nbsp;an immediate lump sum payment equal to the sum of
(A)&nbsp;any unpaid salary and bonus earned for the preceding fiscal year, (B)&nbsp;a pro rata portion of the bonus that would have been paid to the executive had he remained employed until the
end of the fiscal year and as if all performance targets had been met (including the value of any restricted stock granted in lieu of bonus), and (C)&nbsp;two or three times base salary and cash
bonus (depending upon the executive involved) for either the most recently completed fiscal year prior to the termination or the preceding fiscal year, whichever produces the higher amount,
(ii)&nbsp;continued coverage for the executive and his dependents under the Company's welfare and </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>68</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Termination of Employment&nbsp;&#151; Disability:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If the executive's employment terminates due to Disability, the executive will receive payment pursuant
to the Company's disability plans then in effect and will continue to receive coverage under the Company's medical, dental and life insurance plans for three years following such termination. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Acceleration of Equity Awards:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The severance and change in control agreements also provide
that upon any Change in Control, all outstanding stock options and restricted stock will vest immediately. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>For

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>"Change

in the holders of the voting stock immediately prior thereto holding less than 60% of the voting stock of the resulting or surviving entity, (iii)&nbsp;a sale of substantially all of the Company's
assets other than to an entity at least 80% owned by the Company, or (iv)&nbsp;the election, without the consent of the incumbent Board, of the lesser of three directors or a majority of the
directors then in office. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>"Cause"
means the executive's (i)&nbsp;dishonesty, intentional breach of fiduciary duty, or intentional wrongdoing, (ii)&nbsp;disregard of a material and proper direction from the Board, or
(iii)&nbsp;material breach of the agreement that is not cured within 10&nbsp;days of receipt of notice from the Company. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>"Disability"
means a physical or mental condition that has prevented the executive from substantially performing his duties under the agreement for a period of 180&nbsp;days and that is expected to
continue to render the executive unable to substantially perform his duties for the remaining term of the agreement on a full-time basis. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>"Good
Reason" means (i)&nbsp;a material reduction in the nature or scope of the executive's duties or responsibilities, or in his compensation (including benefits), (ii)&nbsp;if Mr.&nbsp;Storch
is not the Chief Executive Officer at the time of termination, the executive's determination that as a result of a material change in employment circumstances he is unable to adequately carry out his
duties, or (iii)&nbsp;a relocation of the executive's primary place of employment by more than 100 miles. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>In
any event, payments under the agreements in connection with termination of employment that would be considered deferred compensation under Section&nbsp;409A of the Internal Revenue Code </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Split Dollar Insurance Agreements  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The Company has entered into split dollar life insurance agreements with certain key employees, including Mr.&nbsp;Storch and Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko.
Under the agreements, the employees own the policies, except for the cash value portion of the policies owned by the Company. The Company funds the annual insurance premiums for the policies during
the term of the agreement subject to reimbursement from the cash value or death benefit proceeds of the policies. Upon a Change in Control of the Company (as defined above), the Company will prepay
all premiums, plus any amounts necessary for the cash value and death benefits to be at the same level at the Change in Control date. If the executive's employment terminates after a Change in Control
and benefits are paid under the severance and change in control agreements, the split dollar agreements will continue for the severance period. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><B><I> Stock Benefit Plan  </I></B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>A named executive officer's termination of employment can result in enhanced benefits under the Company Stock Benefit Plan, depending on the reason
for such termination: </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Stock Options:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If termination is due to Retirement (as defined in the Plan), options continue to vest in accordance with the vesting schedule and can be exercised
until the expiration date, except that if death occurs before the award expires, then unvested stock options are forfeited. If death occurs within three months after Retirement, vested options can be
exercised until the earlier of one year after death or the option expiration date, and if death occurs after three months from Retirement, vested options can be exercised until the option expiration
date. If termination is due to Disability (as defined in the Stock Benefit Plan), options continue to vest and are exercisable until the earlier of one year after termination of employment and the
option expiration date, except that if death occurs before the award expires, then unvested options are forfeited and vested options are exercisable for the period described herein. If death occurs
during employment, or within three months after termination of employment for reasons other than Cause, then unvested options are forfeited and vested options are exercisable until the earlier of one
year after death or the option expiration date. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><I> Restricted Stock Awards:</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If termination is due to Retirement, restricted stock awards continue to vest in accordance with their vesting schedule. If termination is
due to Disability (as defined in the Stock Benefit Plan) or death on or before the third anniversary of the date of grant, then the difference between one-half of the total award shares
and the number of shares already vested will vest as of such termination. If termination is due to Disability or death after the third anniversary of the date of grant, all awards shares will vest as
of such termination. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
Stock Benefit Plan has change in control provisions that apply to participants who do not have a severance and change in control agreement. Upon a Change in Control of the Company (as defined in
the Stock Benefit Plan) that does not have prior written approval of the Board, all options and restricted stock awards will fully vest. Upon a change in control that has the approval of the Board,
the Compensation Committee has the discretion to either provide for full vesting of options and restricted stock awards or grant replacement awards with respect to the successor company's stock. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>70</FONT></P>

 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>1</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Under
the Stock Benefit Plan and severance and change in control agreements, all restricted stock (both performance-based and
time-based) generally vests upon a Change in Control of the Company. See "&#151;&nbsp;Stock Benefit Plan" above. The amounts shown reflect the number of shares that would have
vested upon a Change in Control on May&nbsp;31, 2011, based on the number of shares multiplied by $26.39, the closing price of the Common Stock on May&nbsp;31, 2011.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>2</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Under
the Stock Benefit Plan and severance and change in control agreements, all stock options generally vest upon a Change in Control of the
Company. See "&#151;&nbsp;Stock Benefit Plan" above. The amounts shown reflect the number of option shares, multiplied by the difference (but not less than zero) between the option exercise
price and $26.39, the closing price of the Common Stock on May&nbsp;31, 2011. </FONT></DD></DL>
 </DIV>

<DIV style="padding:0pt;position:relative;text-align:left;margin-left:10%;">
 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>1</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Reflects
continued salary for 36&nbsp;months for Mr.&nbsp;Storch under his employment agreement and continued salary for 12&nbsp;months
for the other named executive officers under their severance and change in control agreements.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>2</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Reflects
(i)&nbsp;in the case of Mr.&nbsp;Storch, three times the average of the non-equity incentive plan compensation or bonus
paid to him for the three preceding fiscal years, and (ii)&nbsp;in the case of the other named executive officers, the non-equity incentive plan compensation bonus paid for Fiscal 2011
as shown in the Summary Compensation Table.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>3</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
amounts in this column reflect the value of the restricted stock that would vest pursuant to the Stock Benefit Plan if termination is due to
Retirement at May&nbsp;31, 2011, based on the number of shares, multiplied by $26.39, the closing price of the Common Stock on May&nbsp;31, 2011. </FONT></DD></DL>

<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>4</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The
amounts in this column reflect the value of the continued vesting of options pursuant to the Stock Benefit Pan if termination is due to
Retirement or Disability at May&nbsp;31, 2011 based on the difference between the exercise price and $26.39, the closing price of the Common Stock on May&nbsp;31, 2011.

under Mr.&nbsp;Storch's employment agreement upon his retirement.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>6</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Available
under Mr.&nbsp;Storch's employment agreement and the severance and change in control agreements for the other named executive
officers.

amounts in these columns reflect the value of the restricted stock that would vest upon termination due to Disability or death at
May&nbsp;31, 2011, based on the number of shares, multiplied by $26.39, the closing price of the Common Stock on May&nbsp;31, 2011. </FONT></DD></DL>

 <DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>1</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Reflects
three times salary for Mr.&nbsp;Storch under his employment agreement and two or three times salary (depending on the officer
involved) for the other named executive officers under their severance and change in control agreements.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>2</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Reflects
(i)&nbsp;in the case of Mr.&nbsp;Storch, the non-equity incentive plan compensation bonus paid to him for Fiscal 2011
as shown in the Summary Compensation Table, plus three times his non-equity incentive plan compensation bonus for either the most recently completed fiscal year prior to termination or the
preceding fiscal year, whichever produces the higher amount (except that upon termination by Mr.&nbsp;Storch for other than Disability or death during the 30-day period following the
24<SUP>th</SUP>&nbsp;month after a Change in Control, Mr.&nbsp;Storch would receive $4,747,770), and (ii)&nbsp;in the case of the other named executive officers, the non-equity
incentive compensation plan bonus paid to them for Fiscal 2011 as shown in the Summary Compensation Table, plus two or three times the non-equity incentive plan compensation bonus
(depending on the officer involved) for either the most recently completed fiscal year prior to termination or the preceding fiscal year, whichever produces the higher amount.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>3</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Includes
an income tax gross-up payment. </FONT></DD></DL>

<A NAME="toc_dy76401_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>   SECURITY OWNERSHIP OF MANAGEMENT AND OTHERS    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The following tables show the shares of Common Stock beneficially owned, as of July&nbsp;31, 2011, by (i)&nbsp;each current director and director
nominee for election to the Board, (ii)&nbsp;each executive officer named in the Summary Compensation Table, (iii)&nbsp;all directors and executive officers of the Company as a group, and
(iv)&nbsp;each beneficial owner of more than five percent of the outstanding shares of Common Stock. Except as noted, the nature of beneficial ownership for shares shown in the tables is sole voting
and sole investment power, and none of the shares shown in the tables is pledged by any of the persons listed. <A NAME="Security_Ownership_of_Man"></A> </FONT></P>

<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>1</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Includes
unvested restricted shares held by directors and executive officers, as well as the following shares of the identified person that may
be acquired within 60&nbsp;days of July&nbsp;31, 2011 through the exercise of stock options: Mr.&nbsp;Brocksmith, 7,000 shares; General Fogleman, 7,000 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Goodwin, 7,000 shares;
Mr.&nbsp;Poulton, 34,079 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Regan, 21,411 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Romenesko, 82,329 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Stinson, 13,332 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Storch, 313,861 shares; Mr.&nbsp;Walfish,
17,000 shares; and Mr.&nbsp;Woodard, 3,500 shares; and all directors and executive officers as a group, 516,512 shares.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>2</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Includes
10,000 shares beneficially owned through Maverick Investors Limited Partnership, a family partnership of which Mr.&nbsp;Boyce is a
general partner.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>3</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Includes
16,000 shares beneficially owned through KMK&nbsp;&amp; Associates,&nbsp;LLC, of which Mr.&nbsp;Kelly is a one-third
owner.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2><SUP>4</SUP></FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Includes
18,810 shares beneficially owned by Mr.&nbsp;Storch's wife, as to which Mr.&nbsp;Storch disclaims beneficial ownership.

 <P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy76401_section_16(a)_benefici__dy702046"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy76401_3"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>  Section&nbsp;16(a) Beneficial Ownership Reporting Compliance    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 requires the Company's officers and directors, and beneficial owners of more than 10% of
the Company's stock, if any, to file reports of ownership and changes in ownership on Forms&nbsp;3, 4, and 5 with the SEC and the NYSE, and to furnish copies of these forms to the Company. To the
Company's knowledge, based solely upon a review of copies of SEC Forms&nbsp;3, 4 and 5 and upon related written representations furnished to the Company with respect to Fiscal 2011, the Company
believes that all of the Company's officers and directors filed on a timely basis all reports required by Section&nbsp;16(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 during Fiscal 2011, except that
Mr.&nbsp;Dany Kleiman, an executive officer of the Company, filed a late Form&nbsp;4 on November&nbsp;18, 2010 to report the sale of 1,706 shares used to pay his taxes in connection with the
release of restricted shares. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="dy76401_other_business"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_dy76401_4"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>   OTHER BUSINESS    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Management knows of no other matters which are to be brought before the annual meeting. However, if any other matter properly comes before the annual
meeting, the named proxy holders will vote all proxies in their discretion and best judgment on such other matter. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ea76401_stockholder_proposals_for_the_2012_annual_meeting"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ea76401_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>   STOCKHOLDER PROPOSALS FOR THE 2012 ANNUAL MEETING    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Any stockholder who, in accordance with SEC Rule&nbsp;14a-8, wishes to present a proposal for consideration at the annual meeting of
stockholders to be held in 2012 must submit such proposal to the Company, in writing, to be received by the Secretary of the Company, AAR CORP., One AAR Place, 1100 N. Wood Dale Road, Wood Dale,
Illinois 60191, no later than May&nbsp;5, 2012, in order for the proposal to be eligible for inclusion in the Company's proxy statement and form of proxy for
that meeting. The proposal must comply with applicable SEC rules and the Company's By-Laws. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Under
the Company's By-Laws, any stockholder who wishes to submit a matter (other than a stockholder proposal brought in accordance with SEC Rule&nbsp;14a-8) for
consideration at the 2012 annual meeting of stockholders, including any stockholder proposal or director nomination, that would not be included in the Company's proxy statement must submit the matter
to the Company, in writing, to be received by the Secretary of the Company no later than April&nbsp;18, 2012. The notice of such matter must contain the information required by the
By-Laws. </FONT></P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2><A
NAME="ha76401_appendix_a__#151;_aar_corp._ca__app03542"> </A>
<A NAME="toc_ha76401_1"> </A>
<BR></FONT><FONT SIZE=2><B>   APPENDIX A&nbsp;&#151; AAR CORP. CATEGORICAL STANDARDS AND POLICY FOR <BR>  DETERMINING DIRECTOR INDEPENDENCE    <BR>    </B></FONT></P>


<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>It is the policy and practice of AAR CORP. (the "Company") that the directors of the Company, when carrying out their duties, must exercise their
independent judgment in good faith and in the best interests of the Company and its stockholders as a whole. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>In
addition, it is the policy of the Company that a majority of its directors, and all directors serving on the Audit Committee, Compensation Committee and Nominating and Governance Committee, shall
be "independent," as determined by the Board in accordance with the independence standards of the New York Stock Exchange ("NYSE"). </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>At
least once each year, the Board shall review the "independence" of each director and any nominee for director and make a determination whether the director or nominee has any material relationship
with the Company (either directly or indirectly as a partner, shareholder, or officer of an organization that has a relationship with the Company) that would impair the director's ability to exercise
independent judgment as a member of the Board. </FONT></P>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>To
assist it in determining a director's "independence," the Board has adopted the following categorical standards for determining director "independence" status with respect to service as a
director*: </FONT></P>

<!-- COMMAND=ADD_LINERULETXT,NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="10%" ALIGN="LEFT" -->
<HR NOSHADE  COLOR="#000000" SIZE="1.0PT" WIDTH="10%" ALIGN="LEFT" >


<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>*</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>The foregoing categorical standards shall be deemed to be automatically updated to reflect any changes made to the
NYSE listing standards and shall be interpreted in the same manner as such standards.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>1.</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>For
purposes of these categorical standards, the "Company" includes each of the Company's subsidiaries and "immediate family member" means a person's spouse,
parents, children, siblings, mothers- and fathers-in-law, sons- and daughters-in-law, brothers- and sisters-in-law,
and anyone (other than domestic employees) who shares the person's home; provided, that any such persons who no longer have any such relationship as a result of legal separation or divorce, or death
or incapacitation, shall not be considered immediate family members.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>2.</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>No
director shall be independent if he/she does not meet the independent standards adopted from time to time by the NYSE. Specifically, a director will </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2><I>not</I></FONT><FONT SIZE=2> be "independent" if: </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT>
<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>the director is or was within the last three years an employee of the Company, or an immediate family member of such
director is or was within the last three years an executive officer of the Company; or  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>the director or an immediate family member of the director receives or received more than $120,000 in direct compensation
from the Company in any twelve-month period with the last three years, other than director and committee fees, and pension or other forms of deferred compensation for prior service (provided such
compensation is not contingent on continued service); provided, however, that compensation received by an immediate family member of a director for service as an employee (other than an executive
officer) of the Company need not be considered in determining independence; or </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
</DD></DL>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>A-1</FONT></P>

<HR NOSHADE>
<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
<!-- ZEQ.=1,SEQ=84,EFW="2205348",CP="AAR CORP",DN="1",CHK=937481,FOLIO='A-1',FILE='DISK131:[11ZDA1.11ZDA76401]HA76401A.;6',USER='GLOPEZA',CD='23-AUG-2011;17:57' -->
<A NAME="page_ha76401_1_2"> </A>

<P style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2><A
HREF="#bg76401a_main_toc">Table of Contents</A></FONT></P>

<UL>
<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>(A) The director or an immediate family member is a current partner of a firm that is the Company's internal or external
auditor; (B)&nbsp;the director is a current employee of such firm; (C)&nbsp;the director has an immediate family member who is a current employee of such firm and who personally works on the
Company's audit; or (D)&nbsp;the director or an immediate family member was, within the last three years (but is no longer), a partner or employee of such firm and personally worked on the Company's
audit during that time; or  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>the director or an immediate family member of the director is or was within the last three years an executive officer of
another company on whose compensation committee any of the Company's present executive officers serves or served; or  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>the director is a current employee, or an immediate family member is a current executive officer of a company that has
made payments to, or received payments from, the Company for property or services in an amount which, in any of the last three fiscal years, exceeds the greater of $1&nbsp;million or 2% of the other
company's consolidated gross revenues (payments to and payments from are compared against the benchmarks separately).
<BR><BR></FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
</UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>3.</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>In
determining director independence, the Board will give consideration to all known relevant facts and circumstances.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>4.</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Notwithstanding
the foregoing, if a director or his/her immediate family member has another significant relationship with the Company that is not described
in Section&nbsp;2, or, at any time, is the subject of a written request by any director to the Chairman of the Nominating and Governance Committee requesting a review of another director's
independent status and stating the reasons therefor, then the Board of Directors will determine whether that director's relationship is a "material relationship" that would impair the director's
ability to exercise independent judgment as a member of the Board.
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>5.</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Members
of the Audit Committee must satisfy the enhanced "independence" criteria under applicable rules of the Securities and Exchange Commission and the New
York Stock Exchange from time to time. In particular, the following enhanced "independence" qualifying criteria shall apply with respect to directors selected for service on the Audit
Committee: </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT>
<UL>
<DL compact>
<DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Director may not have accepted any direct or indirect consulting, advisory or other compensatory fee from the Company
other than amounts received as compensation for membership on the Board or Board committees, pension or other forms of deferred compensation for prior service.  </FONT> <FONT SIZE=2>
<BR><BR></FONT></DD><DT style='font-family:times;margin-bottom:-11pt;'><FONT SIZE=2>&#149;</FONT></DT><DD style="font-family:times;text-align:justify"><FONT SIZE=2>Director may not be an "affiliated person," i.e.,&nbsp;a person who directly or indirectly controls, is controlled by or
is under common control with, the Company (typically, one who is an executive officer or who owns more than 10% of the Company's securities is considered an "affiliated person"). </FONT></DD></DL>
</UL>
</DD></DL>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" style="font-family:times;"><FONT SIZE=2>A-2</FONT></P>

<P style='font-family:times;page-break-before:always'></p>
